move. The Bc8 will be needed to defend the kingside, so b6 only weakens c6. SF5 suggest Kh8, but white seems to be slightly better anyway.

Too passive, now white can start a very strong attack. 14. ... Na5 15. Re1 Re8 war more than enough to equalize.

But white overpresses! 15. Ne5 was very active and would have secured a long-lasting advantage. Note that d5 cannot be captured due to the weakening of a6 field (after exchanging everything the Pa6 remains exposed).
Bad move, which weakens the kingside. After 15. ... Nb5 16. Nxb5 axb5 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Bxh7+ Kh8 18. Ne6 fxe6 19. Qh5 white can get not more than perpetual.
Unjustified. 16. Nge4 would have been enough to keep the advantage but white did not realize that Pd5 is still untouchable.
Error, based on a tactical mistake.

Which black does not punish. After Nf4 the game was over since it will come to great simplifications followed by the loss of Nh7.

Black blunders the checkmate in g7. It would have had the choice between
- 19. ... Qxg2+ 20. Qxg2 Bxg2 21. Kxg2 with a slightly inferior endgame (the piece up of white is the bad Nh7)
- 19. ... g6 20. Rae1 Qxd3 21. Rxe7 Rxe7 22. Sf6+  with repetion of moves (Kg8 cannot go to d file because of Rfd1)
